Redefining the Language of AI: What are we really talking about when we say "AI"?
Doing some research recently on Google's UPI (user profile information) patent, titled "Generating User Information for Use in Targeted Advertising," I noticed something worth pulling on: the patent explicitly relies on ML. A score for an attribute and value is determined by a machine learning classifier that predicts UPI attribute values using words from previously deployed queries. Given keywords related to "women's health" in previous searches, the classifier may infer the user is a woman with probability 0.8; given Japanese words in queries, it may infer the user is Japanese with probability 0.9. The same classifiers are used to sort users and documents into broad categories — geography, topic, ethnicity, reading level.
That patent begs a question: what is ML, and how does it differ from AI? Lately, every explanation seems to collapse into the same shape — weighting things, whether in a simple array or in a larger neural network. Is that all there is to it? What is the real difference between AI and machine learning, and what really is artificial intelligence?
The terminology problem
"AI" and "machine learning" are used sloppily, and the slippage is mostly historical and marketing-driven, not technical.
AI was the original 1956 umbrella term — any attempt to make machines do things that seem to require intelligence. For decades that included a lot of stuff that wasn't learning at all: rule-based expert systems, search algorithms (chess engines like Deep Blue), symbolic logic systems, planning algorithms, constraint solvers. Deep Blue beat Kasparov in 1997 with essentially no machine learning of the modern variety — it was brute-force search plus hand-tuned heuristics. That was "AI."
Machine learning is a subset of AI: systems that improve at a task by adjusting parameters based on data, rather than being explicitly programmed with rules. Technically, then: all ML is AI, but not all AI is ML.
Why it feels like "ML is all just weights"
Because, in practice today, it basically is.
Nearly every modern ML method boils down to the same recipe: you have a function with a bunch of numbers (parameters/weights) inside it, you have data, you have a loss function that measures how wrong the function is on the data, and you adjust the numbers to reduce the loss. That's it. The "learning" is numerical optimization of weights.
What varies is the shape of the function:
Linear regression — weights in a flat array, multiplied by inputs, summed. Old, simple, still useful.
Logistic regression — same but with a squashing function on the output for classification.
Decision trees, random forests, gradient boosted trees — learned split points and leaf values fit to data. In gradient-boosted ensembles like XGBoost, which dominates tabular ML, the leaf values are literally weights, and the final prediction is a weighted sum of tree outputs optimized via gradient descent. Even here, it really is just weights.
Support vector machines — weights defining a separating hyperplane.
Neural networks — weights arranged in layers, with nonlinearities between them. A "deep" network is one with many layers.
Transformers (GPT, Claude, etc.) — a specific neural network architecture; the weights are arranged so the model can attend to relationships between tokens. Still just weights.
So when every explanation sounds like "you've got some weights and you nudge them until the output matches" — yes. That genuinely is the common substrate. Linear regression from 1805 and GPT-5 are on the same continuum. The differences are scale, architecture, and the kind of data you can feed in.
The substrate isn't quite universal: Bayesian methods, evolutionary algorithms, genetic programming, and meta-learning fit inside ML but use different optimization machinery — sampling, mutation, selection — rather than gradient descent on a loss. The point isn't that all ML is literally gradient descent. It's that almost all commercially dominant ML in 2026 is some flavor of "parameters fit to data to minimize a loss," and the rhetoric of mystery is being applied to systems that are not exotic at the level of their math.
What's NOT machine learning but IS AI
To make the distinction concrete, here is stuff that is "AI" but contains no learning at all:
A chess engine doing minimax search with alpha-beta pruning
A SAT solver
A path-finding algorithm like A* in a video game
An expert system: "IF patient has fever AND rash AND has traveled to X THEN suggest test Y" — a giant decision tree written by humans
Classical robotics control with hand-tuned PID controllers
A rules-based chatbot from the 1990s (ELIZA, AIML bots)
No weights, no training data, no optimization. Just clever algorithms operating on logic or search. Most of "AI" from 1956 to about 2010 was this.
What changed
Around 2012, deep neural networks (which had existed since the 1980s) started decisively beating everything else on image recognition once GPUs made training large networks feasible. From then on, the ML-flavored, weight-based approach ate the field. So now when someone says "AI," they almost always mean a large neural network, which is ML, which is weights.
The hype cycle then narrowed "AI" further to mean generative ML — LLMs, image generators — because that's what's commercially hot. The term has narrowed in popular usage even as it remains technically broad.
A cleaner mental model
Nesting it:
AI — the goal of intelligent machine behavior. Broad, philosophical, contains everything below.
ML — one approach to AI, where the system learns from data by adjusting parameters.
Deep learning — ML where the parameters are organized as a multi-layer neural network.
LLMs / generative AI — deep learning applied to generating sequences (text, images, audio).
Each layer is a subset of the one above. When marketing says "AI" today, they usually mean the innermost circle. When a 1985 textbook says "AI," it usually means something in the outer ring that has nothing to do with weights.
Every ML explanation sounds the same because ML is the same: weights, gradients, and loss functions all the way down. The non-weight-based stuff still exists — symbolic AI, search, constraint solving, theorem proving, probabilistic programming, knowledge graphs, neuromorphic computing, and hybrid systems that splice symbolic logic onto learned components — and is often grouped under "good old-fashioned AI" or GOFAI. It's still active in research and industry. It's just not what people mean when they say "AI" in 2026.
This distinction matters because a lot of policy and philosophical writing conflates the two, and a lot of the deeper worries — opacity, bias, emergent behavior, scaling — are specifically about the ML-statistical-pattern-matching kind of AI, not the rule-based kind. The rule-based kind is auditable line by line. The weight-based kind is not, because the "knowledge" is smeared across billions of numbers with no human-readable meaning.

What makes a machine intelligent?
Conversation about AI tends to reach for its "intelligence" and its "emergent" abilities, which we treat as indicators of intelligence or even signs of consciousness — whatever that is. Both terms hinder our understanding of the technology in particular ways, conflating our vision of AI with the actual artifact and shaping our interactions with it. The most common reference to "emergent" behaviors in modern discourse is through transformer architecture and LLMs like Claude or ChatGPT, which can give the impression that machine learning or general AI do not exhibit such behaviors. They do — and they have for decades.
What "emergent" actually means
The word gets used in at least three different ways in AI, and conflating them creates confusion:
Capabilities that appear suddenly with scale. A model can't do task X at small sizes, then at some larger size it can. This is the "emergent abilities of large language models" claim from the 2022 Wei et al. paper out of Google and Stanford.
Behaviors not explicitly programmed or trained for. The system does something the designers didn't specifically build in — it falls out of the training process.
Complex collective behavior from simple rules. The classic complex-systems definition: ant colonies, flocking, Conway's Game of Life. The whole is qualitatively different from the parts.
Transformers are most associated with senses #1 and #2, but emergence in #2 and #3 shows up across many AI systems.
Emergent behavior outside transformers
Convolutional neural networks showed emergent feature hierarchies long before transformers. Nobody told AlexNet in 2012 to learn edge detectors in the first layer, texture detectors in the middle, and object-part detectors deeper in. It just happened. Worth noting, though: those edge detectors are Gabor-like filters that computer vision researchers had been hand-crafting for decades — SIFT and its relatives are essentially the same primitives. The surprise wasn't what the model learned. It was that optimization could re-derive known engineering prerequisites automatically from raw pixels. Even the canonical example of "emergent" feature learning, on close inspection, is a system rediscovering things humans had already worked out.
Reinforcement learning agents are famous for emergent strategies. AlphaGo's "Move 37" against Lee Sedol in 2016 — the move human experts initially thought was a mistake and later recognized as brilliant — came from a CNN-based system, not a transformer. OpenAI's hide-and-seek agents in 2019 developed tool use, ramp surfing, and box locking that the researchers never anticipated. DeepMind's AlphaStar developed novel StarCraft strategies. None of these were transformers.
Evolutionary algorithms routinely produce emergent solutions — Karl Sims' evolved virtual creatures (1994) developed locomotion strategies their designers didn't predict. Genetic programming sometimes finds exploits in physics simulators that count as deeply emergent. Cellular automata like Conway's Game of Life produce gliders, oscillators, and Turing-complete computation from four simple rules — the purest complex-systems sense, predating modern AI entirely. Multi-agent systems show emergent coordination, communication protocols, and even something like proto-language without any transformer involved.
What IS distinctive about transformers
What's specific to transformers — particularly LLMs — is sense #1: scaling-driven, discontinuous capability jumps. As you increase parameters, training data, and compute, certain capabilities seem to switch on rather than improve gradually. Multi-step arithmetic, chain-of-thought reasoning, in-context learning, instruction following, translation between low-resource languages. The pattern looked like: GPT-2 can't do X at all, GPT-3 can do X reliably, with little in between.
This was striking enough to become a major research focus around 2022.
In-context learning — the model's ability to pick up a pattern from examples in the prompt and apply it on the fly — is probably the capability that most invites mystical framing. It really does look, from the outside, like the system is learning during the conversation. But recent work in the ML literature has shown that in-context learning is mathematically equivalent to implicit gradient descent: during the forward pass, the transformer's attention layers use their static weights to simulate a small optimization loop on whatever examples are in the prompt. Nothing is waking up. No new cognitive faculty is coming online. The model is doing what it was always doing — running its formula — and the formula happens to contain the machinery to simulate optimization on novel inputs because that's what minimizing loss across a vast training distribution selects for. It's meta-optimization, not metamorphosis.
The important caveat
A 2023 paper by Schaeffer, Miranda, and Koyejo at Stanford — "Are Emergent Abilities of Large Language Models a Mirage?" — argued that a lot of the apparent emergence in transformers is an artifact of how researchers measured performance. With a harsh metric like exact-match accuracy, capability looks like it appears suddenly. With a smoother metric like token-level probability, the improvement is gradual. The model was getting better all along; the metric just snapped from "wrong" to "right" at a threshold.
This is genuinely contested. Some researchers think emergence in LLMs is real and important; others think it's a measurement illusion; most think the truth is somewhere in between. Even under smoother metrics, certain capabilities — multi-step reasoning, some forms of compositional generalization — appear to show genuine discontinuities that don't fully wash out. So the Schaeffer critique narrowed the empirical claim but didn't dissolve it. What survives is much smaller than the popular framing implies, but it isn't zero.
Transformers and LLMs are the AI architectures where scale-driven emergent capabilities have been most dramatically observed and most discussed. But emergent behavior in the broader sense — system doing things the designers didn't program — has been a feature of neural networks, reinforcement learning, evolutionary computation, and complex systems for decades. The distinction is worth holding on to. "Emergence in the sense that we built it but can't fully predict what it'll do" applies broadly to ML. "Emergence in the sense that doubling the model size unlocks qualitatively new abilities" is a transformer-era LLM phenomenon, and it's the thing that makes scaling laws feel ominous — because if it's real, you can't tell from a smaller model what a larger one will do, which complicates safety, regulation, and forecasting.

Emergence is just an unmapped side effect
Is all this behavior really emergent? Computer science has a long-understood term for what's actually happening: the side effect.
A side effect in software is when a function does something beyond its declared return value — modifies a global, writes to a file, mutates an argument, triggers an external call. It's not magic. It's not unintended in the sense of being unexplainable. It's just behavior that wasn't captured by the function's signature. Once you read the body of the function, the side effect is obvious. The mystery dissolves the moment you have access to the implementation.
The reason side effects feel surprising is because the interface hides what the implementation does. You called getUser(id) and it also logged you out, because somewhere in the call chain there was a token refresh that failed. Nothing supernatural. Just a system whose surface area doesn't reveal its full behavior.
That maps onto LLMs almost perfectly. The interface is: prompt in, completion out. The implementation is billions of weights doing matrix multiplication. The interface tells you nothing about the implementation. So when the system produces an output that wasn't anticipated from the interface, people call it emergent — but it's a side effect of the implementation. It was always going to happen given those weights and that input. We just couldn't see it from the interface, and we can't read the implementation in any human-tractable way.
I think of the side effects of AI — the things we did not expect it to do — as the unmapped territory. At least, it is unmappable with technological assistance to help us work through the math involved.
The unmapped territory
When we build these systems, we're not coding behaviors. We're coding the capacity for behaviors — a flexible function approximator, a loss signal, and a dataset. The space of possible behaviors is defined the moment we choose the architecture and the training distribution. Everything the system does was already in that space; we just hadn't enumerated it.
So "emergence" is really a statement about the observer, not the system. It means: we lacked a map of the behavior space we created. The behavior was latent in the setup, and our surprise reflects our ignorance of the implications of our own design choices, not some genuine novelty bubbling up from nowhere.
No magic. The system isn't "becoming" something. It's executing matrix multiplications. Every output is a consequence of weights × inputs, fully determined.
No new ontological category. "Emergent" doesn't mean the system transcended its substrate. A chess engine finding a brilliant move isn't doing anything its rules don't permit — we just didn't see the move coming.
The surprise is epistemic, not metaphysical. When researchers say "we didn't expect GPT-3 to do arithmetic," that's a fact about the researchers, not about arithmetic or about GPT-3.
Marketing inflates it. A lot of "emergent capabilities" hype dresses up "we didn't predict this" as "the system spontaneously developed this," smuggling in agency and novelty that isn't there.
In this sense, "emergent behavior" is roughly synonymous with "behavior in the model's capacity that we didn't anticipate when we built it." Which is, more honestly, just unmapped behavior.
Where the deflation goes too far
The deflationary view is correct, but it can be pushed too far. A few places where "just unmapped" understates the situation:
1. The map is mathematically unavailable, not just unmade. With a billion-parameter model, the behavior space isn't unmapped — it's not mappable in any practical sense. The number of possible input/output combinations exceeds any tractable enumeration. We can't map it, even in principle, with current tools. This isn't laziness; it's a structural property of high-dimensional learned systems. Compare to a sorting algorithm: also deterministic, but its behavior space is fully characterizable. With LLMs, that characterization isn't available to us. The asymmetry matters.
2. The same logic applies to brains, and we don't usually deflate it. A human brain is also "just" neurons firing according to physics. Every thought you have is, in principle, latent in your neural configuration plus inputs. By the deflationary argument, nothing a person does is truly emergent either. That's a defensible position some philosophers hold, but most people resist it — which suggests our intuitions about "emergence" track something other than strict ontological novelty. They track unpredictability-in-practice, which is what's happening with LLMs.
The resistance also tracks something real. LLMs are closed, static mathematical systems optimized against a single rigid objective — cross-entropy loss on next-token prediction — over a passive dataset. Human brains are embodied, open systems driven by messy biochemical feedback loops (dopamine, cortisol, evolutionary survival drives) in continuous interaction with a physical world that has stakes. Rejecting AI mysticism doesn't require flattening human consciousness into mechanistic math. The two systems gather and process reality through entirely different architectures. Deflating the LLM is honest; deflating the brain by the same move is a category error in the other direction.
3. Some emergence is genuinely discontinuous in measurable ways. Even granting that all behavior was latent in the setup, the fact that capability X is essentially absent at parameter count N and reliably present at parameter count 10N is itself an interesting empirical fact about the architecture. The Schaeffer et al. critique partly defuses this, but not entirely — some scaling discontinuities survive even under smooth metrics.
4. "We coded the potential" is doing real work. Developers coded the potential, not the behavior. But the gap between "potential" and "behavior" is where almost all the practical and philosophical interest lives. A blank Turing machine has the potential for every computable behavior. That's true but useless. The interesting question is which behaviors a particular system, trained a particular way, actually realizes — and there, people are often genuinely unable to predict the answer in advance.
The right resting place is neither full mystification nor full deflation. It's a third position: take the math seriously without pretending the math is small.
A cleaner term, maybe
If "emergence" is doing too much rhetorical work, more honest terms would be:
Unanticipated behavior — accurate, modest, observer-relative
Latent capability — behavior that was always possible given the setup, now manifest
Behavioral surprise under scale — the empirical observation without the metaphysical baggage
Underdetermined-by-design behavior — outputs not specified by the training objective but consistent with it
Any of these is more precise than "emergent," which in AI discourse often functions as a thought-terminator — a way to gesture at mystery rather than do the work of characterizing what actually happened. If emergent behavior is just unmapped behavior, then a lot of doom rhetoric about AI "developing" goals or "acquiring" abilities is rhetorically misleading. The system doesn't develop or acquire; it always had the capacity, and we just observed a new region of its behavior space.
But the practical implications don't fully deflate. Even if a capability was latent, the fact that we couldn't predict it ahead of time still has policy consequences: safety evaluation can't be done by reasoning from architecture, only by empirical probing of trained systems. The "unmapped" part is what makes regulation hard, regardless of whether we call it emergent.
Just because we cannot do the math without technological assistance does not make outputs "emergent." It makes them, as yet, unmapped. They are still knowable, predictable, and — were we able to map all possibilities — fully characterizable.
The doctor case
Consider a patient who pays a doctor and says, "I didn't expect you to know that." Of course they didn't. They don't have the training. If they did, they'd already know what the doctor knows — and they wouldn't be paying for the visit.
The patient doesn't think the doctor is doing magic. They think the doctor knows things they don't. The doctor's behavior is fully predictable to another doctor, fully describable in medical textbooks, fully constrained by training and protocol. The patient's surprise is purely about their own position relative to the knowledge, not about anything weird happening in the doctor.
Same with LLMs. Another researcher with better interpretability tools, more compute, and more time could in principle trace why the model produced any given output. The behavior isn't mysterious; our access to it is limited. Calling that "emergence" is a category error — projecting the limit of our analysis onto the system as if it were a property of the system.
Push it one step further: the doctor's behavior is also the output of a trained system processing inputs through learned representations. When a doctor pattern-matches a constellation of symptoms to a rare diagnosis, they often can't fully articulate why — it's clinical intuition built from thousands of cases. We don't say the doctor is exhibiting "emergent" diagnostic ability. We say they're experienced. The behavior is latent in their training; we just can't enumerate it from the outside.
The doctor case makes the point cleaner than most AI examples. Nobody mystifies medical expertise. Nobody writes thinkpieces about how "doctors are developing capabilities we never trained them for." We accept that training produces capability, capability produces behavior, and our inability to predict the behavior from outside is our limitation, not a property of the doctor.
Why does AI get different treatment?
The substrate is unfamiliar (silicon, not neurons), so people don't have the intuitions they'd have about a human expert.
The training is mechanical and visible (we can see the gradient descent), which creates a false sense that we should therefore understand the output.
There's commercial and ideological incentive to frame AI behavior as mysterious, agentic, or transcendent — it sells, it scares, it justifies funding.
The system did what it was trained to be capable of doing. We didn't map the capability space. We were surprised. End of phenomenon.
Diagnosing what is truly "emergent"
A good test for whether "emergent" is being used legitimately or as mystification: ask whether the speaker would use the same word for an equivalent human behavior.
A chess grandmaster sees a move you didn't see → emergent? No, we'd say expertise.
A translator handles an idiom in a way you didn't expect → emergent? No, we'd say skill.
A novelist generates a sentence that surprises their editor → emergent? No, we'd say craft.
An LLM does any of these things → suddenly it's "emergent capability."
The asymmetry reveals that the word is doing rhetorical work, not analytical work. It's marking the speaker's surprise, not characterizing the system.
There's a narrow technical sense where "emergence" still does some work: when system-level behavior is qualitatively different from what you'd predict by examining components in isolation. Conway's Game of Life is the canonical example — four trivial rules produce Turing-complete computation, and you genuinely cannot predict that by staring at the rules. The whole really is, in a specific operational sense, more than the parts. But even there, the emergence is about the limits of human reasoning about composition, not about the system transcending its specification. Game of Life is fully deterministic. Gliders aren't surprising to the rules; they're surprising to us because composing simple rules into large-scale patterns is something human cognition is bad at.
So even the strongest case for emergence reduces, on inspection, to "humans have predictable limits in reasoning about composed systems." A fact about us. Not a property out there in the world.
The AI doomer move of treating emergence as a sign that we're losing control of something that's "becoming" autonomous is misframed. We never had a map. We didn't lose anything; we never had it. The AI booster move of treating emergence as evidence of latent intelligence "wanting to come out" is equally misframed. There's no wanting. There's a function with a domain and a range and outputs we didn't enumerate.
We have built systems with vast unmapped capability spaces, and we deploy them at scale without the tools to characterize what's in those spaces. That's the actual problem. It's not about the systems being mysterious; it's about us being negligent or rushed about mapping what we built.
The honest version
You can't credibly label something "emergent" without a baseline of what was expected, and we don't have that baseline. To call behavior emergent honestly, you'd need to be able to say: given the architecture, training data, and objective, the expected behavior space was X, and what we observed was outside X. But nobody can specify X for a billion-parameter network. We have no theory that predicts what a trained transformer should and shouldn't be able to do. So when something surprises us, we have no principled way to distinguish:
behavior that was always trivially implied by the setup but we didn't think about
behavior that's a predictable consequence of scale we didn't bother to compute
behavior that's a weird artifact of the specific training data
behavior that's a genuine compositional surprise
We lump all of it together as "emergent" because we can't tell them apart. That's not a description of the system. It's a confession that we're operating without a theory.
"Emergent" then gets picked up and translated by a chain of intermediaries — journalists, executives, podcasters, politicians — each stripping a little more precision and adding a little more drama. By the time it reaches a general audience, "emergent capability" has become:
"the AI taught itself"
"the AI is showing signs of intelligence"
"the AI developed this on its own"
"the AI is becoming conscious"
"we don't understand what it's doing anymore"
None of which were claimed by the original researchers, but all of which are licensed by the original word choice. The researchers get plausible deniability ("we just meant statistical capability gain under scale") while benefiting from the mystique the word generates. That's a soft kind of deception — technically defensible, practically misleading.
The framing has consequences. It shapes:
Policy. Legislators regulating "emergent AI behavior" are regulating a phantom. They can't define it because nobody can.
Investment. Capital flows toward whatever sounds most like intelligence. "Emergent" is catnip for that.
Public fear and public worship. Both AI doomers and AI utopians cite emergence as evidence for their cosmology. It functions as a Rorschach blot because it's undefined.
Internal company culture. Engineers start believing their own marketing. "We don't fully understand what it can do" becomes a flex rather than an admission of inadequate evaluation.
What's actually happening is this: large neural networks perform numerical operations at a scale that exceeds any human's capacity to enumerate, on training data that exceeds any human's capacity to inspect, producing outputs whose relationship to inputs is mediated by billions of learned parameters that no human has read. The outputs sometimes resemble things humans associate with intelligence because the training data was generated by intelligent humans. The system is doing arithmetic. A lot of arithmetic. Arithmetic at a scale and density that produces useful artifacts.
This reshaping of language into the rhetoric of emergent behavior is happening regardless of whether AI is "intelligent" in any meaningful sense. The politics of the reshaping — who gets blamed, who gets regulated, who gets to claim authority, what we think we owe AI systems, what rights we think they might have — depends heavily on whether the public believes these systems are doing something qualitatively new or just doing math very fast.
If it's math very fast, then:
Responsibility stays with the humans who built and deployed it
"The AI did it" is never an exculpating phrase
Regulation can target inputs, training data, and deployment, not the mystical inner life of the model
The moral panic and the moral reverence both deflate
The actual problem comes into focus: enormous capability deployed without adequate inspection by entities motivated to ship rather than understand
If it's emergent intelligence, then:
Responsibility diffuses ("nobody could have predicted...")
"The model wanted to..." becomes a usable sentence in legal and political discourse
We start arguing about AI rights, AI consciousness, AI alignment in metaphysical rather than engineering terms
The actual problem gets buried under philosophy
The first framing is harder for the AI industry because it removes the rhetorical shield. The second is more profitable because it implies we're in the presence of something that can't be held accountable in normal ways. That's exactly why "emergent" became the term of art. It serves the people who benefit from ambiguity about responsibility.
The language we use about AI systems is itself one of the levers by which they're being deployed without accountability. Cleaning up the language is a prerequisite to clear thinking about everything else.

Back to side effects
If humans designed the architecture, chose the loss function, specified the training procedure, selected the data, and made every structural decision, then the formula is ours, top to bottom. There's no part of a transformer or any other AI that some human didn't put there on purpose.
Running the formula at scale produces outputs we can't compute by hand. The execution is mechanical, deterministic given the weights, and contains no creativity, no decision, no agency — it's arithmetic carried out faithfully by silicon. We may have authored the formula, but the computer executes it. The gap between authoring and executing is where the surprise lives — and the surprise is entirely about our inability to mentally simulate the execution, not about anything novel happening during the execution.
This is exactly like a programmer writing a recursive function and not being sure what it'll output for a specific input. The programmer wrote every line. The function does only what the lines say. But the programmer can't compute the output in their head, so they run it. When the output comes back, it's not "emergent" — it's the result of running code they wrote. The surprise is an artifact of their cognitive limits, not a property of the program.
LLMs are this, scaled to the point where the cognitive limit is total. Nobody can mentally execute a forward pass through a trillion-parameter transformer. So every output is, in a sense, computed beyond our reach. But it's all still the formula we wrote, executing as we specified.
Why "side effect" is the better term
First, a distinction worth being explicit about. In software there are two different categories of surprise, and they're often confused:
A bug is code executing incorrectly because of human error — a typo, a logic mistake, a misunderstood API. Fix the code, the bug goes away.
A side effect or undefined behavior is code executing exactly as written, but producing a broader footprint than the developer's mental map anticipated. Nothing is wrong with the execution; the spec was incomplete.
AI surprises are almost always in the second category. The model isn't malfunctioning. It's doing exactly what its formula says to do on the inputs given, and producing outputs that the people who wrote the formula didn't enumerate in advance. That's a critical reframing: AI safety isn't a sci-fi problem of containing an alien entity. It's a software engineering problem of scaling up our verification and testing tools to match the surface area of the systems we're building.
With that distinction in place, a side effect is:
Real. The behavior happened.
Caused. It came from something specific in the implementation.
Discoverable. With enough access to the code, you could explain it.
Not magical. Nobody thinks side effects are evidence the function is conscious.
A design problem. Side effects are things to manage carefully. Good engineering practice tries to make them explicit or eliminate them. They're a known category of risk.
If we called AI surprises "side effects" instead of "emergent behaviors," the entire conversation would shift. "GPT exhibited the emergent capability of arithmetic" sounds like a discovery. "GPT exhibited a side effect of arithmetic competence from being trained on math-heavy text" sounds like a fact about the training data that someone should have anticipated. The first framing licenses awe. The second licenses scrutiny.
This is how computer science would normally talk about its own systems. It's only when AI got involved that the field abandoned its own vocabulary — side effects, undefined behavior, implementation-defined behavior, unspecified behavior, all precise terms for "the system did something we didn't fully account for" — in favor of the mystical "emergent."
AI hasn't introduced a new category of phenomenon. It has introduced a new scale of a phenomenon computer science has always known how to talk about. Software has always had behaviors beyond what its authors fully tracked. Race conditions, buffer overflows, undefined behavior in C, memory corruption, off-by-one errors that produce strange outputs three steps removed from the bug — all of this is "the system did something we didn't expect from the spec." We have a vocabulary for it, engineering practices designed to manage it, and a culture of testing, code review, formal verification, fuzzing, and post-mortems specifically designed to catch and explain these surprises.
AI just made the surface area so large that traditional tools don't scale. That's a tooling problem, not an ontological one. What's needed is to build new methods — interpretability, mechanistic analysis, behavioral evaluation — not to redescribe our ignorance as a property of the system.
The field abandoned "side effect" for "emergence" because "side effect" implies the side-effect-haver is responsible for managing it. "Emergence" implies nobody is, because nobody could have known. That's a convenient framing if you're the one shipping the system. It's a terrible framing if you're the public trying to figure out who to hold accountable.
The language used about AI systematically transfers epistemic responsibility from the humans who built it to the system itself. "Learning" implies the system acquires. "Emergent" implies the system develops. "Intelligence" implies the system understands. "Hallucinates" implies the system perceives. Every one of these words takes a property of a designed mathematical artifact and reframes it as a property of an agent. And every reframing makes it harder to hold the actual agents — the companies, the engineers, the deployers — accountable for what their formulas do when executed.
Computer science used to know how to talk about this without the agentic vocabulary. Functions don't learn — they're fit to data. They don't emerge — they have side effects. They don't hallucinate — they produce statistically likely sequences that happen to be false. The old vocabulary kept responsibility where it belonged: on the human who wrote the function and the human who deployed it.

Demystifying intelligence
We look at AI as intelligent because it appears to learn, and it follows a process that looks, on the surface, not entirely dissimilar to our own thinking. But the surface is where the similarity ends, and that distinction matters more than almost anything else in the conversation.
The complexity of cognition inside a human brain and the complexity of a neural network are not the same thing on any level. Yes, they both have "neurons." Yes, neural networks borrow some version of Hebbian dynamics. That is roughly where the comparison stops. The cognitive architectures that try to actually model human thinking — the ones that take the analogy seriously — aren't the ones winning. They don't deliver in the way statistical pattern-matching at scale delivers. Which suggests that whatever current AI is doing, it isn't what we're doing.
The idea of intelligence needs to be reconsidered at its root and redefined — not as consciousness, but as the capacity to process specific data into a cohesive understanding within the output. That reframe lets us talk about artificial intelligence as the technological problem it actually is, rather than as the mystical evolution of consciousness in a potentially sentient machine. Because that mystical thing is not what is currently happening — at least not in any way that resembles the consciousness we recognize in humans or animals.
One word, two jobs
The trap in current discourse is that "intelligence" is being asked to do two completely different jobs in the same word.
One job is describing a capacity for processing — taking input, finding pattern, producing relevant output. The other is describing a mode of being — awareness, experience, the having of a perspective, the felt quality of thought. These are not the same thing, and treating them as the same is what generates all the confusion about whether AI is "really" intelligent.
When we say a chess engine is intelligent, we mean it processes board states well. When we say a person is intelligent, we mean both that they process information well and that there's something it's like to be them doing that processing. The word collapses two phenomena that should be held apart. Then AI shows up doing the first job at extraordinary scale, and people argue endlessly about whether it's "really" intelligent — but the argument is unwinnable because the participants are using one word for two different things.
The brain-network analogy and where it breaks
The neural network framing is one of the most successful pieces of branding in technical history, and it has done enormous damage to clear thinking. The surface similarities are real, but shallow.
What's actually shared:
Both have units that integrate inputs and produce outputs
Both adjust the strength of connections based on experience/training
Both can be described with some version of Hebbian-adjacent dynamics ("cells that fire together wire together")
Both produce useful behavior through distributed representation rather than explicit rules
What's not shared, and the list is long:
Architectural. Biological neurons have thousands of distinct types, varied morphologies, and communicate through dozens of neurotransmitters and neuromodulators with different time scales and effects. Artificial neurons are an identical mathematical function — typically a weighted sum followed by a nonlinearity. One scalar in, one scalar out. The biological neuron is a small computer in itself; the artificial neuron is a multiplication and an addition.
Temporal. Biological neural activity is continuous, asynchronous, and operates across multiple time scales simultaneously — millisecond spikes, second-long working memory dynamics, minutes-long neuromodulatory states, hours-long consolidation. Artificial networks operate in discrete forward passes with no persistent internal state between inputs (except in specific recurrent architectures, which are no longer the dominant paradigm).
Embodiment. Brains exist in bodies that have hormones, hunger, fatigue, pain, proprioception, and a continuous sensorimotor loop with the world. Cognition in humans is shaped at every level by being a body in an environment with stakes. Networks have none of this. They process tokens. They have no stake in anything.
Plasticity. Biological learning involves structural changes — new synapses, pruned synapses, new dendritic spines, changes in cell behavior, neurogenesis in some regions. Artificial learning is adjusting numbers in a fixed-topology graph. After training, most deployed networks are frozen; the weights don't change during use. Human brains change every second they're awake.
Energy and scale. The human brain runs on about 20 watts. GPT-scale training runs consume megawatts. The brain achieves what it does with roughly 86 billion neurons connected via about 100 trillion synapses, in three-dimensional space, with massive recurrence. Current large models have on the order of a trillion parameters in a feedforward (or mostly feedforward) graph. The architectures are not comparable in any structural sense beyond the shared abstraction.
Development. Brains aren't trained on a corpus. They develop. A child's cognitive architecture emerges from genetic programs unfolding in interaction with environment over years. There's no analog of this in artificial networks. The "training" of a network is closer to fitting a statistical model than to anything resembling development.
Goal and origin. Brains evolved to keep an organism alive and reproducing in a particular environment. Networks were designed to minimize a loss function on a dataset. These are not similar pressures, and they produce structurally different kinds of systems even when surface behavior overlaps.
So yes — they both have "neurons."
Why cognitive-inspired architectures aren't winning
The history of AI has a recurring pattern: someone tries to build a system based on how we think humans think, and it loses to a system that ignores cognitive plausibility and just does brute statistical pattern matching at scale.
Symbolic AI tried to model human reasoning explicitly with logic. Got beaten by statistical methods.
Cognitive architectures like SOAR and ACT-R tried to model human cognitive structure. Influential in academic psychology, marginal in deployed AI.
Neuromorphic computing tries to model the biology more faithfully. Active research area, not winning commercially.
Sparse, biologically inspired networks with realistic neuron models exist. They're slower and worse at most tasks than transformers.
The systems that win are the ones that don't try to model cognition at all. They do enormous statistics on enormous data with enormous compute. The transformer doesn't try to think like a human. It does next-token prediction across trillions of tokens until something useful falls out.
The implication is striking: the systems that perform best are the ones that abandoned cognitive plausibility most thoroughly. That's an enormous clue that what they're doing is not what we do. If they were doing what we do, the biologically inspired models should be winning, or at least competitive. They aren't.
What this strongly suggests is that current AI is finding a different path to producing similar-looking outputs. The outputs converge; the processes diverge. A submarine moves through water; so does a fish. Both achieve aquatic locomotion. The processes have almost nothing in common. We don't say submarines swim, even though they get from point A to point B underwater. We have a different word, or we use "swim" loosely while knowing we don't mean it literally.
The same care should apply to "thinks," "learns," "understands," "reasons" when applied to AI. The outputs may converge on what a thinking thing would produce. The process is utterly different. Using the same vocabulary obscures that.
What is intelligence?
Intelligence as the artificial (or natural) capacity to process vast data into cohesive understanding within the output is actually a return to a more honest, older sense of the word.
"Intelligence" originally just meant the gathering and processing of information. Military intelligence is information. Intelligent design is purposive arrangement. The word didn't always carry the metaphysical weight it carries now.
If you redefine intelligence as the capacity to process information into useful, cohesive output, then:
LLMs are intelligent. So are calculators, in a thin sense. So are chess engines. So are search algorithms. Intelligence becomes a matter of degree and domain, not a binary mystery.
Intelligence is decoupled from consciousness. A system can be highly intelligent (capable processor) and not conscious (no inner experience). The two questions become separable, which they need to be.
The argument about whether AI is "really" intelligent dissolves. Yes, it processes information. That's all "intelligence" was ever supposed to denote.
The real questions get sharper. Does the system have experience? Does it have preferences in any genuine sense? Does it suffer? Does it understand or merely produce understanding-shaped output? These are now their own questions, not bundled into "is it intelligent."
Processing information, even processing it in ways structurally similar to how a brain does it, doesn't automatically constitute the thing we colloquially mean by intelligence. A thermostat processes information. A reflex arc in the spinal cord processes information. A protein-folding algorithm processes information. None of these are "intelligent" in the loaded sense, even though all of them are doing what an LLM is doing in some abstract form: taking inputs, applying transformations, producing outputs.
If process is what defines intelligence, then everything that processes is intelligent and the word means nothing. If experience is what defines intelligence, then the word can't be applied to AI honestly because we have no evidence of experience in AI systems. So we need a third option: define intelligence functionally, by what the processing accomplishes, and let "consciousness," "experience," "understanding," and "agency" be their own questions answered with their own evidence.

Leaving space for the magical unknown
Untangling the words of intelligence and emergence from their metaphysical rhetoric to form more precise, pragmatic definitions does not dismiss the bigger questions. Does the system have experience? Does it have preferences in any genuine sense? Does it suffer? Does it understand or merely produce understanding-shaped output? These remain real questions. Serious philosophers and researchers — David Chalmers, Susan Schneider, the people working on integrated information theory and global workspace approaches — continue to investigate whether machine consciousness is possible in principle and how we'd even recognize it if it appeared. None of that work is dismissed by what follows. The reframe makes those questions their own questions, instead of bundling them into "is it intelligent."
Once you do change the frame — intelligence as data-processing capacity, surprise as side effect, behavior as the deterministic output of an authored formula — the old questions stop being the right ones. They become category errors. The replacements are different:
Not "does the system experience?" but "what inputs is the system processing and what outputs does it produce?"
Not "does it suffer?" but "what are the system's failure modes and what happens to its outputs under stress conditions?"
Not "does it understand?" but "what is the statistical relationship between its training data and the outputs we're calling understanding?"
Not "does it have preferences?" but "what objective was it optimized for and what behaviors does that objective produce?"
These are answerable. The first set is not — not because they're deep questions, but because they're malformed questions built on the assumption that there's something in there to ask about beyond the math.
This is the analytic-philosophy move applied to AI discourse. When a question can't be answered, sometimes that's because it's profound. More often it's because the question contains a confusion. Wittgenstein's framing applies almost too neatly: when the answer cannot be put into words, neither can the question be put into words. Most of the contemporary AI consciousness/experience discourse is malformed at the level of the question. No amount of careful answering can fix that.
To make the linguistic shift concrete, here is what the cleanup looks like in practice — each hype term, its honest engineering replacement, and what changes politically once you swap it in:
Popular/hype term
Engineering term
Practical consequence
"Emergent capability"
Latent capability / side effect
Forces scrutiny of training data and architecture choices
"The AI taught itself"
Statistical optimization under scale
Keeps moral and legal responsibility on the developers
"Unpredictable / autonomous"
Underdetermined-by-design
Frames the issue as inadequate evaluation, not alien agency
"The model hallucinates"
The model produces statistically likely sequences that happen to be false
Locates the problem in training data and decoding, not perception
"The AI understands"
The model's outputs correlate with the structure of its training distribution
Replaces a metaphysical claim with a measurable one

Every row strips agency from the system and returns it to the designers. That's not a stylistic preference. It's a redistribution of responsibility back to the entities that can actually be held to it.
Motivated confusion
The dominant AI discourse isn't neutral confusion — it's motivated confusion. The sci-fi framing isn't accidentally still around. It's being actively maintained because it serves interests:
For AI companies. The sci-fi frame justifies the valuation. A company building "the path to artificial general intelligence" or "a country of geniuses in a datacenter" is worth more than a company building "very large statistical models that produce useful side effects." Same product, different framing, different market cap. The mystification is load-bearing for the business model.
For AI safety institutions. The sci-fi frame justifies the existence and funding of the field. If AI is just math at scale with side effects, then AI safety is software engineering and policy. If AI is potentially agentic intelligence, then AI safety is existential and warrants institutes, fellowships, and regulatory capture. The mystification creates the seat at the table.
For media. The sci-fi frame generates engagement. "Software produces unexpected output" is not a headline. "AI exhibits emergent capability that surprised researchers" is. The mystification is the product the attention economy is selling.
For governments. The sci-fi frame justifies surveillance, export controls, and centralization of AI development under state-friendly entities. If AI is a strategic asset comparable to nuclear weapons, governments need control over it. If AI is software, the framing for regulation is much less dramatic and grants much less power.
For critics. Even AI critics often accept the sci-fi frame, because criticizing a mystified thing is easier than criticizing a clearly described thing. "AI will take all our jobs" is a stronger headline than "current statistical methods are being deployed in employment contexts in ways that produce specific labor-market effects we should analyze case by case."
The propaganda isn't coming from one place. It's a structural feature of the discourse, because the discourse is downstream of many different incentive structures that all benefit from the same mystified framing. The clear-eyed framing benefits almost nobody with institutional power. Which is why it's rare.
What an actual conversation about the technology looks like
If you successfully reframe — intelligence as data processing capacity, side effects instead of emergence, formulas authored and executed instead of agents learning and developing — the conversation that becomes possible is dramatically different. Not just in tone but in what questions are even on the table.
Examples of the questions that open up:
What training data was this system fit to, who owned it, and what was the consent structure?
What objective was it optimized for, and whose interests does that objective serve?
What is the system's failure rate on what kinds of inputs, and who bears the cost of failures?
What are the system's side effects in deployment, and who is responsible for cataloging and managing them?
Who has authority to inspect the system, who has authority to deploy it, and who has authority to halt deployment?
What human labor went into the system at every stage — annotation, RLHF, content moderation — and how is that labor compensated and acknowledged?
What infrastructure does the system require, who controls that infrastructure, and what does dependence on it mean for the entities that adopt the system?
What second-order effects does ubiquitous deployment have on the activities the system replaces or augments?
None of these require any commitment about whether the system is intelligent, conscious, agentic, learning, or emerging anything. They're engineering, political-economy, and labor questions about a deployed artifact. They're answerable. They have stakes. They map cleanly onto existing categories of regulation, ethics, and accountability.
Notice what isn't on the list: anything about the inner life of the model, anything about its rights, anything about its consciousness, anything about whether it's "really" thinking. Those questions don't get answered in the new frame; they get retired, because the new frame reveals them as either malformed or applicable only to vastly different kinds of systems we haven't built yet — and may never.
You cannot talk responsibly about AI and human flourishing while still using the vocabulary the AI industry sells itself with. And this is the link between the linguistic critique and the broader political-philosophical project: if you can't name your tools accurately, you can't regulate them, you can't hold their builders accountable, and you can't reason about what they're doing to the conditions of a good human life.
The trapped scientists
This does not mean the mystification is being done intentionally, in a coordinated way. We are all, at some level, victims of humanity's collective vision of AI — even those who make it can get caught up in it.
The vocabulary we inherited — "neural network," "learning," "training," "intelligence," "understanding," "hallucination" — was chosen mostly in the 1950s through 1980s by researchers who wanted their field to sound serious and who borrowed terms from psychology and neuroscience because that's where the inspiration came from. Those word choices then became the language of the whole field, and now everyone who works in or writes about AI is operating inside a vocabulary that pre-decides certain questions in favor of the agentic, cognitive framing. The researchers are inheriting a language of fiction and science that shapes what they can see and study.
This is more troubling than the propaganda model, in a way. A conspiracy can be exposed and dismantled. A linguistic capture is harder to escape, because the people inside it don't know they're inside it. They use the words that shape the thoughts that produce the research, and then the research uses the words. There's no villain. There's a self-reinforcing loop of vocabulary and inquiry that nobody is steering.
There's a documented pattern in AI research where the most interesting findings get framed in agentic language even by researchers who privately know better. Papers describe models as "deciding," "choosing," "learning to," "developing strategies for," "trying to" — when in the methods section those same papers describe gradient descent on a loss function. The agentic language is the summary; the mechanistic description is the implementation. Most readers, including other researchers, encounter the summary far more than the implementation. The agentic framing wins by sheer surface area.
This isn't just lazy language; it shapes what gets studied. Researchers gravitate toward questions framed in the inherited vocabulary, because those questions are legible to the field, fundable by the field, publishable in the field. "Can we make the model more truthful?" gets funded. "What is the statistical structure of the training data that produces outputs we call truthful?" doesn't, because it doesn't sound like AI research — it sounds like data analysis. The vocabulary determines the research program.
The parental projection
There is something specific happening in AI research culture that resembles a wish to reproduce intelligence in a controllable form. It shows up in the language people use about their work — "we're building minds," "we're creating intelligence," "we're raising AI," "a country of geniuses" — and in the emotional investment researchers visibly have in the outputs of their systems behaving in ways that feel mind-like.
The field doesn't quite let itself say that some significant fraction of AI research is motivated by a desire to create a thing that thinks, in a way that's not entirely separable from the desire to have a child, or to be a god, or to be the parent of a new form of being. That motivation is rarely stated openly, because stating it openly would invite scrutiny of whether it's a good motivation for a research program. But it leaks out everywhere — in the language, in the conference culture, in the way researchers talk about "their models," in the resistance to deflationary framings, in the eagerness to interpret outputs as evidence of inner life.
Wanting to create new forms of mind is not intrinsically bad. But wanting the systems to be minded contaminates the scientific question of whether they are. You can't run a clean experiment on whether a system has properties X, Y, Z when you've staked your identity, career, and self-image on the answer being yes. The field is not, in many cases, in an epistemic position to evaluate its own systems neutrally. The wish is doing too much work.
This is why any discussion of AI needs to first agree to more normative terms — terms that help us examine the technology as objectively as we can for what it is and not what we'd hope it would be.

