Works cited in the chapter
Patents
Bharat, K., Lawrence, S., & Sahami, M. (2003, filed; 2016 granted). Generating user information for use in targeted advertising. U.S. Patent No. 9,235,849 B2. Assigned to Google Inc. Available at https://patents.google.com/patent/US9235849B2
The patent describes how user profile information (UPI) can be inferred from past search queries and document selections using machine learning classifiers and graph-based inference. It is the document whose explicit reliance on ML inference of demographic attributes opens the chapter.
Emergence and scaling
Wei, J., Tay, Y., Bommasani, R., Raffel, C., Zoph, B., Borgeaud, S., Yogatama, D., Bosma, M., Zhou, D., Metzler, D., Chi, E. H., Hashimoto, T., Vinyals, O., Liang, P., Dean, J., & Fedus, W. (2022). Emergent abilities of large language models. Transactions on Machine Learning Research. arXiv:2206.07682.
The paper that popularized the claim that LLMs exhibit discontinuous capability jumps with scale. Defines an "emergent ability" as one not present in smaller models but present in larger ones. Co-authored across Google Research, Stanford, UNC Chapel Hill, and DeepMind.
Schaeffer, R., Miranda, B., & Koyejo, S. (2023). Are emergent abilities of large language models a mirage? Advances in Neural Information Processing Systems 36 (NeurIPS 2023). Outstanding Paper Award. arXiv:2304.15004.
The critical reply to Wei et al. Argues that many apparent emergent abilities are artifacts of nonlinear or discontinuous evaluation metrics; when measured with smoother metrics, the same capabilities improve gradually. The paper that narrowed (but did not eliminate) the empirical case for emergence.
Kaplan, J., McCandlish, S., Henighan, T., Brown, T. B., Chess, B., Child, R., Gray, S., Radford, A., Wu, J., & Amodei, D. (2020). Scaling laws for neural language models. arXiv:2001.08361.
The foundational paper on how model performance scales predictably with parameters, data, and compute. Useful background for the "continuous improvement" side of the emergence debate.
In-context learning as implicit gradient descent
Dai, D., Sun, Y., Dong, L., Hao, Y., Ma, S., Sui, Z., & Wei, F. (2023). Why can GPT learn in-context? Language models implicitly perform gradient descent as meta-optimizers. arXiv:2212.10559. Microsoft Research and Peking University.
Argues that transformer attention has a dual form of gradient descent, and that in-context learning is best understood as implicit fine-tuning — the model uses its static weights to simulate optimization on the examples in the prompt. The technical basis for the claim in the chapter that ICL is meta-optimization rather than a "new cognitive faculty."
von Oswald, J., Niklasson, E., Randazzo, E., Sacramento, J., Mordvintsev, A., Zhmoginov, A., & Vladymyrov, M. (2023). Transformers learn in-context by gradient descent. Proceedings of the 40th International Conference on Machine Learning. arXiv:2212.07677.
A complementary paper showing constructively how linear self-attention can implement one step of gradient descent, with empirical confirmation that trained transformers learn solutions matching this construction. Reinforces the "implicit optimization" framing.
Convolutional networks and feature learning
Krizhevsky, A., Sutskever, I., & Hinton, G. E. (2012). ImageNet classification with deep convolutional neural networks. Advances in Neural Information Processing Systems 25 (NIPS 2012), pp. 1097–1105.
The AlexNet paper. Demonstrated that GPU-trained deep convolutional networks could decisively beat hand-crafted feature pipelines on ImageNet. The point of reference for the chapter's discussion of "emergent" feature hierarchies — and for the observation that the edge detectors it learned were the same Gabor-like filters humans had been hand-crafting for decades (e.g., in SIFT).
Lowe, D. G. (2004). Distinctive image features from scale-invariant keypoints. International Journal of Computer Vision, 60(2), 91–110.
The SIFT paper. The hand-crafted descriptor that AlexNet's first-layer filters effectively re-derived from raw pixels. Useful for showing that the "emergent" features were known engineering primitives.
Evolutionary computation and emergent behavior
Sims, K. (1994). Evolving virtual creatures. SIGGRAPH '94: Proceedings of the 21st Annual Conference on Computer Graphics and Interactive Techniques
The classic demonstration that evolutionary algorithms produce locomotion strategies the designer didn't anticipate. The reference for the chapter's argument that emergent-style behavior predates transformers by decades.
Reinforcement learning
Silver, D., Huang, A., Maddison, C. J., Guez, A., Sifre, L., van den Driessche, G., Schrittwieser, J., Antonoglou, I., Panneershelvam, V., Lanctot, M., et al. (2016). Mastering the game of Go with deep neural networks and tree search. Nature, 529(7587), 484–489.
The AlphaGo paper. Source for "Move 37" against Lee Sedol.
Baker, B., Kanitscheider, I., Markov, T., Wu, Y., Powell, G., McGrew, B., & Mordatch, I. (2020). Emergent tool use from multi-agent autocurricula. International Conference on Learning Representations. arXiv:1909.07528.
The OpenAI hide-and-seek paper. Source for the emergent tool use, ramp surfing, and box locking strategies cited in the chapter.
Vinyals, O., Babuschkin, I., Czarnecki, W. M., Mathieu, M., Dudzik, A., Chung, J., et al. (2019). Grandmaster level in StarCraft II using multi-agent reinforcement learning. Nature, 575(7782), 350–354.
The AlphaStar paper.
Chess (pre-ML AI)
Campbell, M., Hoane, A. J., & Hsu, F.-H. (2002). Deep Blue. Artificial Intelligence, 134(1–2), 57–83.
The technical retrospective by Deep Blue's architects. Useful for verifying the claim that Deep Blue's success came from massive parallel search and hand-tuned evaluation, with no significant machine learning component of the modern variety.
Cellular automata and complex systems
Gardner, M. (1970). Mathematical games: The fantastic combinations of John Conway's new solitaire game "life." Scientific American, 223(4), 120–123.
The original popular introduction to Conway's Game of Life. Referenced in the chapter as the canonical example of emergence in the strongest complex-systems sense — Turing-complete computation from four trivial rules.
Rendell, P. (2002). Turing universality of the game of life. In A. Adamatzky (Ed.), Collision-based computing. Springer.
The construction of a universal Turing machine inside Game of Life, confirming the formal claim that the cellular automaton is computationally complete.

Further reading (not cited but worth pursuing)
On the philosophy of mind and machine consciousness
Chalmers, D. J. (1996). The conscious mind: In search of a fundamental theory. Oxford University Press.
The foundational text on the "hard problem of consciousness." Useful for grounding the chapter's claim that consciousness and intelligence are separable questions.
Chalmers, D. J. (2023). Could a large language model be conscious? Boston Review, August 9, 2023. Also published as arXiv:2303.07103.
A direct, balanced treatment of the question the chapter mostly brackets. Chalmers takes the question seriously without overclaiming, which is the position the chapter's "Leaving space for the magical unknown" section is gesturing at.
Schneider, S. (2019). Artificial you: AI and the future of your mind. Princeton University Press.
A philosopher's careful treatment of machine consciousness, including proposed tests and the limits of behavioral evidence.
Dennett, D. C. (1991). Consciousness explained. Little, Brown and Company.
The functionalist counterweight. Dennett's position is closer to the chapter's deflationary framing of intelligence-as-processing, though Dennett applies it to consciousness itself in ways the chapter does not.
On AI vocabulary and rhetoric
Bender, E. M., Gebru, T., McMillan-Major, A., & Shmitchell, S. (2021). On the dangers of stochastic parrots: Can language models be too big? Proceedings of the 2021 ACM Conference on Fairness, Accountability, and Transparency (FAccT '21), pp. 610–623.
The "stochastic parrots" paper. A precursor to the chapter's argument about linguistic mystification — Bender and Gebru explicitly push back on agentic vocabulary applied to language models. The paper that got Gebru pushed out of Google.
Mitchell, M. (2019). Artificial intelligence: A guide for thinking humans. Farrar, Straus and Giroux.
A clear, non-mystifying overview of what AI systems do and don't do, written for general readers. Closer in spirit to the chapter's framing than most popular AI books.
Marcus, G., & Davis, E. (2019). Rebooting AI: Building artificial intelligence we can trust. Pantheon.
A skeptical view of deep learning's reach, arguing for hybrid symbolic-neural approaches. Useful for the chapter's acknowledgment that AI is broader than deep learning, even if the chapter takes a different rhetorical route.
On the history of AI
Nilsson, N. J. (2009). The quest for artificial intelligence: A history of ideas and achievements. Cambridge University Press.
The standard scholarly history, covering symbolic AI through the early statistical learning era. Useful background for the chapter's "AI was the original 1956 umbrella term" framing.
Russell, S. J., & Norvig, P. (2020). Artificial intelligence: A modern approach (4th ed.). Pearson.
The canonical AI textbook. The taxonomy of AI techniques — search, logic, planning, probabilistic reasoning, learning — is laid out clearly here. Worth consulting to verify that "AI" properly includes much more than deep learning.
On interpretability and the unmapped territory
Olah, C., Mordvintsev, A., & Schubert, L. (2017). Feature visualization. Distill. https://distill.pub/2017/feature-visualization/
